feed.title: Moths of Riddells Creek
feed.subtitle: Initial list and photos from Peter Marriott. Lots of other ID help from Peter, Marilyn Hewish and Wendy Moore.

entry.title: Aenetus eximia
entry.content: This record extends its known distribution, being the westernmost record of the species in Victoria. Third pic shows yellow wing underside of the female. The two wing spots are also a feature of the female.

entry.title: Hepialidae spp.
entry.content: On wet, warmish autumn nights we get hundreds of rain moths - 17 on this window pane. Mostly O. dirempta/lyelli but occasional O. antipoda (or australis) and T. atripalpis. Tawny Frogmouths feast on them.

entry.title: Abantiades labyrinthicus
entry.content: Never convinced of IDing this species. Could be another Abantiades spp.. Very large moth - perhaps the largest species we get.

entry.title: Endoxyla encalypti

entry.title: Glyphipterix chrysoplanetis
entry.content: Tiny sedge moth in large numbers on Senecio linearifolius var. linearifolius.

entry.title: Chrysolarentia correlata
entry.content: Distinctly yellow in flight and on landing. Gives a few wing flaps on landing before resting. This species might merge with C. insulsata (see CD that comes with Moths of Victoria 3). New species record for Riddells Creek.

entry.title: Aenetus ligniveren
entry.content: Found dead on the garden path this morning. Apparently males are rarely seen. New species record for Riddells Creek.

entry.title: Taxeotis intextata
entry.content: Looks like T. mimela but I'm told more likely to be T. intextata which was seen flying on this night. At a sheet setup during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night.

entry.title: Praxis edwardsii
entry.content: New species record for Riddells Creek - at a sheet setup during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night.

entry.title: Chlorocoma sp. (3)
entry.content: New species record for Riddells Creek - near a sheet setup during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night. Identified using the Emerald moth key in the newly published 'Moths of Victoria 4'.

entry.title: Epidesmia hypenaria
entry.content: Wings held so moth looks triangular. Very long nose.

entry.title: Pollanisus viridipulverulenta
entry.content: About double the size of the similar-looking Turneriprocris dolens, which was flying on the same day - see previous observation, 7802.

entry.title: Leucochrysum albicans var. albicans, Turneriprocris dolens
entry.content: Moth is about half the size of the similar-looking Satin-green Forester, which was also about in large numbers this day (see following observation, 7803). T. dolens seen primarily on the Leucochrysum.
